our approach is to rely on 
1. epoch starts
2. make sure we rely on what executors we discover from the list the miner is advertising to us
3. ensure they are online and indeed belong to the advertised miner
4. remove offline executors (that used to belong to that miner).

tl;dr;
- gpu assignments weren't being deleted when we were deleting the offline executors, resulting to a reassignment in case the same `<miner_uid>__<executor_id>` was coming online
- when we're reporting the GPUs per miner, due to the non deletion of the GPU assignments (of offline executors), those GPUs were included too in the count, although the executors were missing (cleared by the clean-up process we have since the last release)

this is a regression bug, since yesterday's release. the reason why it failed to be shown in our tests, is because we don't have multiple executors and miners in our testnet setup. we only tested the simple happy path.

tl;dr; a cache invalidation mechanism wasn't happening fast enough.

I've been monitoring the activity of some miners, using the `./scripts/validator/investigate.sh` (the script is also also committed) since yesterday, which successfully brought to my attention that the fast switching between online/offline executors, has been leaving a room for arbitrage.

The gpu-assignments and executors tracking update processes have been working well, and we can see the executors going offline within 5-15mins, but the miner's gpu_profile table (which holds a summary of the miner's GPU latest profile) wasn't being updated as fast. Leaving  the mentioned room for arbitrage, and as a result the miner could receive incentives, although we had already seen their executor going offline.

The main change to tackle this, is to make sure the event of observing an executor going offline or failing a GPU validation, to be updating the DB throughout.
